entry.title: snap-group: Correct drop target bounds for the `OverviewGroupItem`
entry.content:
The bounds for the drop target should match the item which the drop

target is a placeholder for. It should also be applicable for group

item. This cl does the following things to make it work:

1. Update the logic in

`OverviewGrid::CalculateWidthAndMaybeSetUnclippedBounds()` where

the width for the drop target widget is calculated;

2. Update `IsDropTargetWindow()` to `IsDropTargetItem()` in order to

take the overview group item into account;

3. Update the insets value in `OverviewGroupItem` anonymous space, to

only have insets in the middle.

entry.title: Optimize several things about DOM Parts [1/2]
entry.content:
See [1] for details. This CL makes these changes:

- Stop maintaining “live” parts lists across DOM mutations. This is

controlled by a new feature flag, DOMPartsAPIActivePartTracking,

that when disabled, short-circuits all of the part list maintenance

code during DOM mutations. This means that if DOM nodes that are

connected to parts are moved around in the DOM, including being

removed from the document, the cached parts list does not change.

- Update ToV8HelperSequence to work directly with Deques, and get

rid of getParts() code to convert to a HeapVector.

- Optimize ToV8HelperSequence to use iterators instead of array

indexing, which should also speed up all sequence bindings. (TBD)

- Change from FrozenArray to sequence. This eliminated

the overhead of Object::SetIntegrityLevel(), which was ~29% of the

total getParts() time.

- Add a fast path for PartRoot.replaceChildren when all children

are being removed.

- Inline IsValid().

- Call InsertBefore() instead of before() to avoid some extra

validity checks. This required making ConvertNodeUnionsIntoNode

public.

- Add PartRoot.getPartNode(n), which allows direct access to a

single Part's Node, to avoid wrapping up the entire parts list.



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wSbBV6tS-KLlHWxaK_FmEJFOwkY-pb8_YDoFJgDrbMg/edit

entry.title: Move some directionality code from HTMLElement to Element.
entry.content:
This change moves a bunch of directionality-related methods from

HTMLElement to Element. This is needed to fix a number of bugs related

to directionality inheritance and dir=auto text traversal when non-HTML

elements are involved.



This change tries to make the minimal change needed to move the code;

other changes will be in later CLs. In particular, this change does the

following:



* moves member functions UpdateDirectionalityAndDescendant,

UpdateDescendantHasDirAutoAttribute, ResolveAutoDirectionality,

AdjustDirectionalityIfNeededAfterChildrenChanged, and

UpdateAncestorWithDirAuto, and the enum UpdateAncestorTraversal, from

HTMLElement to Element, updating their qualified names as needed

* moves file-scope function RecalcSelfOrAncestorHasDirAuto

from html_element.cc to element.cc (this will become a member function

in a later CL)

* adds a single DynamicTo near the start of

UpdateDirectionalityAndDescendant in order to call

UpdateDescendantDirectionality (it could be a To<> in this CL, but in

later CLs it will need to be DynamicTo<>).

* exposes IsValidDirAttribute and ElementIfAutoDirShouldUseValueOrNull

as static members of HTMLElement rather than functions in

html_element.cc

* qualifies to calls to HTMLElement static members from callsites that

are now in Element

* adds an explicit instantiation of ResolveAutoDirectionality in

element.cc to avoid linker errors when compiling html_element.cc

* changes HTMLElement::CalculateAndAdjustAutoDirectionality from

protected to public so it can be called from Element

* move two \#includes from html_element.cc to element.cc

* adds a forward declaration of TextControlElement in html_element.h



The order of the code in element.cc (adjacent to existing directionality

code there) is designed to put general directionality code first, and

then dir=auto specific code after.



The basic idea behind what moves is that I'm moving the code that needs

to move in order to support directionality inheritance and dir=auto text

traversal on all elements. This leaves things that support the dir

attribute (which is only on HTML elements) in HTMLElement. It also

leaves some code that will be removed when the CSSPseudoDir flag is

shipped.



This CL should not cause any behavior changes.

entry.title: android: Allow Paint Preview to happen with native
entry.content:
The decision whether to display the Paint Preview depends on the

heuristic detecting cold start: the start is considered _not_ cold (i.e.

warm) when the native library has already been loaded and initialized.



We hypothesize that recently the library started becoming initialized

very early in the process lifetime. One of the causes for it is

asynchronous library loading on a separate thread.



As a result of recent changes, the volume of UMA samples for

"Browser.PaintPreview.TabbedPlayer.TimeToFirstBitmap" has dropped

dramatically, leading to Paint Preview becoming less useful.



This change attempts to use another heuristic for a cold start:

1. the app process creation is caused by an activity

2. no activity is paused prior to pre-inflation of the tabbed activity



The (1) uses a new "process creation reason" trick available on P+

devices and falls back to time-based detection for older devices.

entry.content:
Reland notes: Fixed presubmit test failures in

Specifically updating:

rollup notes:

With the latest version of Rollup, bundled files are unfortunately a

bit larger, due to fixing a previous bug [1], which incorrectly only

kept the first line of all license header comments. The new behavior

is correct (see updated tests), so perhaps we should look into ways of

deduplicating license header comments in the future, to further reduce

the file size.



svgo notes:

- Latest version includes a fix for [2] which was affecting some SVG

files, and has resulted in using 'minifyStyles: false' in

tools/resources/svgo.config.js as a workaround, see [3].

- Updated svgo.config.js to account for the breaking change at [4].

- Updated svgo_presubmit_test.py since it now re-arranges

the order of SVG attributes as part of the optimization.

entry.title: Deduplicate batched cookie access details
entry.content:
With this CL, we use a std::set to ensure that we avoid sending

IPCs with redundant cookie access details. Some clients care about

counts, so we include a count along with the deduplicated details.



The order of the elements are determined by the position that the

last duplicate would have occupied in the non-deduplicated list.

Eg, consider the following:



ABACCABACDA

^ ^^^

The caret is below the last instance of each duplicated entry. We

take the elements with the carets and return them in this order:

BCDA.



I also noticed that the cookie list was not used in OnCookiesRead

so I've removed that plumbing in this patch as well.



credit: dtapuska@ for suggesting that we avoid storing redundant

data, suggesting a dictionary-like data with counts, and checking

for compression percentage. jbroman@ for suggesting std::tie/

make_tuple for combining r and l values for comparison.

renderer process attempts to classify the page, but the classifier was

80% to 90%, we will wait for the ScorerStorage object to populate with

scorer object has not been updated till the end of the waiting time,

then we will mark with "Classifier Not Ready" for

entry.title: [text-spacing-trim] Avoid redundant entries in features
entry.content:
This patch fixes two redundant operations:

1. `ShapeSegment` can run multiple times for the same range

when there are font cascading or fallback. `HanKerning`

adds features each time, causing redundant entries.

This patch fixes this by resetting the `FontFeatures`,

similar to what `CapsFeatureSettingsScopedOverlay` does.

2. `ShapeSegment` gives the whole range given to `Shape`, not

the range of the segment it is currently shaping. This lets

`HanKerning` to scan the same text multiple times.



These redundancy is not observable, as HarfBuzz ignores

redundant font features, other than the unnecessarily wasted

time and memory.



The `FontFeature` argument is changed from a reference to a

pointer because `HanKerning` will keep the pointer until it

is destructed.



This patch has no behavior changes.
